title: 入力をやわらかく支援する布キーボード (An Assistive Input Device with Soft Texture)
title_en: An Assistive Input Device with Soft Texture
abstract: 本研究はVDT作業での長時間キーボード使用による腕・手・指の疲労や腱鞘炎などの健康問題に対処するために、表面を布地とした布キーボードを提案している。布キーボードはポリウレタン布と5mmスペーサを用いて押下衝撃と急激な押下圧力変化を吸収し、赤外線走査式タッチパネルで位置を検知することで入力衝撃の軽減と打鍵感のカスタマイズを可能にしている。
abstract_en: This study proposes a fabric-surfaced keyboard to address fatigue and tendon problems from long-term VDT keyboard use. The fabric keyboard uses polyurethane cloth and a 5mm spacer to absorb keystroke impact and sharp pressure changes while detecting position with an infrared scanning touch panel to enable reduced input shock and customizable key feel.
positioning_summary: 本研究はVDT作業の普及に伴う長時間キーボード使用による腕や手や指の疲労や腱鞘炎といった健康問題に対処することを位置づけとしている。 本研究は従来キーボードの大きなストロークや急激な押下圧力変化、長時間の無理な姿勢が負担を生む点を問題視しており、これらの負担を軽減する点を研究の中心に置いている。
positioning_summary_en: This study is positioned to address health problems such as fatigue in the arms, hands, and fingers and tendonitis that arise from long-term VDT keyboard use. This study identifies large key travel, sudden changes in keypress force, and prolonged awkward postures of conventional keyboards as sources of burden and focuses on reducing those burdens.
purpose_summary: 本研究はキーボード入力時のキーダウン衝撃を軽減し、長時間作業者が楽な姿勢と好みの打鍵感を得られる入力環境を提供することを目的としている。 本研究は押下圧力とストロークに起因する負担の軽減とキー配列やホームポジションのカスタマイズ性向上を目標にしている。
purpose_summary_en: This study aims to reduce keystroke impact and provide an input environment that allows long-duration users to adopt comfortable postures and preferred key feel. This study specifically targets reduction of burdens caused by keypress force and key travel and aims to improve layout and home-position customization.
method_summary: 本研究は赤外線走査式タッチパネル枠上にポリウレタン布を張った布キーボードの試作機を構築し、布の弾力と5mmスペーサで押下時の衝撃と急激な押下圧力変化を吸収して位置を検知する方式を採用している。 本研究は検出範囲約304mm×230mm、検出点数約100×75の走査枠とプリント可能な布キートップ、入力確認用のスピーカやLEDを備え、布の重ね合わせやスペーサ調整でストロークと押下圧力をカスタマイズ可能とした。
method_summary_en: This study prototyped a fabric keyboard by mounting polyurethane cloth over an infrared scanning touch-panel frame and used cloth elasticity plus a 5mm spacer to absorb keystroke impact and sudden pressure changes while detecting position. This study implemented a scanning frame with a detection area of about 304mm × 230mm and about 100 × 75 detection points, included printable fabric keytops and speaker/LED feedback, and allowed customization of travel and force via cloth layering and spacer adjustment.
evaluation_summary: 本研究は被験者を用いたユーザビリティテストで布キーボードを既存の2種のキーボードと比較して評価した。 本研究は被験者6名による62文字入力の所要時間と主観的評価を測定する方法で評価を行い、評価では従来キーボードが所要時間で有利だったがホームポジションの追加などカスタマイズにより所要時間が約30%短縮され、参加者の多くがカスタマイズ性を高く評価した結果が得られた。
evaluation_summary_en: This study evaluated the fabric keyboard through a usability test comparing it with two existing keyboards using human participants. This study measured completion time for 62-character input and subjective impressions with six participants and found that conventional keyboards were faster in completion time but that adding a home position and other customizations reduced completion time by about 30% and that most participants rated the customization features highly.

Title: An Assistive Input Device with Soft Texture
Authors: Rieko Otsuka, Takeshi Hoshino, Youichi Horry
Year: 2005
Abstract: This study proposes a fabric-surfaced keyboard to address fatigue and tendon problems from long-term VDT keyboard use. The fabric keyboard uses polyurethane cloth and a 5mm spacer to absorb keystroke impact and sharp pressure changes while detecting position with an infrared scanning touch panel to enable reduced input shock and customizable key feel.
Positioning Summary: This study is positioned to address health problems such as fatigue in the arms, hands, and fingers and tendonitis that arise from long-term VDT keyboard use. This study identifies large key travel, sudden changes in keypress force, and prolonged awkward postures of conventional keyboards as sources of burden and focuses on reducing those burdens.
Purpose Summary: This study aims to reduce keystroke impact and provide an input environment that allows long-duration users to adopt comfortable postures and preferred key feel. This study specifically targets reduction of burdens caused by keypress force and key travel and aims to improve layout and home-position customization.
Method Summary: This study prototyped a fabric keyboard by mounting polyurethane cloth over an infrared scanning touch-panel frame and used cloth elasticity plus a 5mm spacer to absorb keystroke impact and sudden pressure changes while detecting position. This study implemented a scanning frame with a detection area of about 304mm × 230mm and about 100 × 75 detection points, included printable fabric keytops and speaker/LED feedback, and allowed customization of travel and force via cloth layering and spacer adjustment.
Evaluation Summary: This study evaluated the fabric keyboard through a usability test comparing it with two existing keyboards using human participants. This study measured completion time for 62-character input and subjective impressions with six participants and found that conventional keyboards were faster in completion time but that adding a home position and other customizations reduced completion time by about 30% and that most participants rated the customization features highly.
